'''Kasuga Mandala''' (春日曼荼羅) refers to a series of {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|mandala|ja|曼荼羅図|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} paintings depicting {{ill|Kasuga Taisha|ja|春日大社|1=Kasuga-taisha|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and related themes, created from the late {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} through the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. 

The mandalas were influenced by the {{ill|Fujiwara clan|ja|藤原氏|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}'s veneration of their {{ill|ujigami|ja|氏神|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} Kasuga Taisha, as well as by the concept of {{ill|Shinbutsu-shūgō|ja|神仏習合|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism). Their production flourished particularly during the {{ill|medieval period|ja|中世|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}). 

Prominent examples include:
* '''Deer Mandala''' (鹿曼荼羅, Shika Mandara): Featuring the sacred deer of Kasuga Taisha. This type is said to have originated from a vision experienced by {{ill|Konoe Motomichi|ja|近衛基通|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>According to the *Heian Period Historical Encyclopedia* entry on "Kasuga Mandala."</ref>
* '''Honji Mandala''' (本地曼荼羅, Honji Mandara): Depicting the {{ill|honji-butsu|ja|本地仏|1=Honji_suijaku#Honji Buddha|lt=Honji Buddha|2=ja|3=本地垂迹|4=fr|5=Honji suijaku|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (original Buddhist counterparts) of the deities enshrined at Kasuga Taisha.
* '''Shrine Mandala''' (宮曼荼羅, Miya Mandara): Featuring Kasuga Taisha and Wakamiya Shrine, with the Five Honji Buddhas as the main focus, set against the background of {{ill|Kasugayama|ja|春日山 (奈良県)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* '''Temple-Shrine Mandala''' (社寺曼荼羅, Jinja Tera Mandara): Incorporating both Kasuga Taisha and its associated temple, {{ill|Kōfuku-ji|ja|興福寺|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* '''Kashima Deity Procession Painting''' (鹿島立神影図, Kashima-Tachi Shinkage-zu): Depicting the divine descent of the deity {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|タケミカヅチ|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Kashima Shrine|ja|鹿島神宮|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} to Kasuga Taisha.

As reverence for Kasuga Taisha expanded beyond the Fujiwara clan to a broader audience, particularly in {{ill|Nara|ja|奈良|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, additional derivatives like the "Suijaku Mandala," "Honjaku Mandala," "Jizō Mandala," and "Pure Land Mandala" emerged.

